.TH STRINGS(1),User Commands,STRINGS(1)

.SH NAME
strings - print printable character sequences from files

.SH SYNOPSIS
strings [-fh] [-n length] [-t {d,x}] file ...

.SH DESCRIPTION
strings reads each named file and prints every run of at least length consecutive printable bytes, one run per output line.
A byte is printable if it lies in the range 0x20..0x7E.
The default minimum run length is 4.

At least one file operand is required;
strings does not read from standard input.

When -t is given, the file offset of the start of each run is printed before the run itself.
When -f is given, the filename is printed before each run.

.SH OPTIONS
-f: Print the name of the file before each string.

-n length: Minimum run length (default 4).
length is parsed as decimal, or hex with a leading $ or 0x.

-t d: Print the byte offset of each run in decimal.

-t x, -t $: Print the byte offset of each run in hexadecimal.

-h: Print a short usage summary and exit 0.

.SH LIMITS
Up to 16 file operands may be given on a single command line.

.SH DIAGNOSTICS
strings: missing file operand - no file was given.

strings: error opening file 'X', code #:NN - a named file could not be opened.

.SH EXIT STATUS
0: All files processed.

1: No file was given, a file could not be opened, or an invalid option was supplied.
